## Program 1: Method Overloading - abs() methods

```java
// MyClass.java
public class MyClass {
    
    // Default constructor
    public MyClass() {}
    
    // abs() for integer
    public int abs(int n) {
        return (n < 0) ? -n : n;
    }
    
    // abs() for float (overloaded)
    public float abs(float n) {
        return (n < 0) ? -n : n;
    }
    
    // abs() for double (overloaded)
    public double abs(double n) {
        return (n < 0) ? -n : n;
    }
}

// Driver1.java
public class Driver1 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        
        MyClass obj = new MyClass();
        
        // Testing abs() with integer
        int intVal = -25;
        System.out.println("Absolute value of integer " + intVal 
                           + " = " + obj.abs(intVal));
        
        // Testing abs() with float
        float floatVal = -3.75f;
        System.out.println("Absolute value of float " + floatVal 
                           + " = " + obj.abs(floatVal));
        
        // Testing abs() with double
        double doubleVal = -9.99;
        System.out.println("Absolute value of double " + doubleVal 
                           + " = " + obj.abs(doubleVal));
    }
}
```

### Output:
```
Absolute value of integer -25 = 25
Absolute value of float -3.75 = 3.75
Absolute value of double -9.99 = 9.99
```

